Hi Bob,

I&#39;ll comment on the /&#39;...developer had implemented System.exit(n) 
throughout the application whenever there was a trapped exception...&#39; 
/later, but for now here&#39;s how to write your tests...


Given this kind of class......



public class SomethingThatCallsExit {

    public int add(int num1, int num2) {
         if( num1 &lt; 0) {
           System.exit(2);
        }

       return num1 + num2;
    }

}


When trying to test it we need to provide a substitute  (delegate) for 
it to call System.exit(); on, instead of doing it itself, so that we 
dont call System.exit during our test runs.


Lets create the Interface that our delegate will need to implement....

public interface SystemExiter {
  void exit(int reason);
}


Now lets create a Fake implementation of the interface for use within 
our tests.

public class FakeSystemExiter implements SystemExiter {

   public boolean   wasExitCalled;
   public int exitReason = -999;  // number not used by our app so other 
tests know if it was set

   public void exit(int reason) {
      wasExitCalled = true;
      exitReason = reason;
   }
}


Now lets create the real implementation....


public class RealSystemExiter implements SystemExiter {

   public void exit(int reason) {
      System.exit(reason);
   }
}


So now we have the necessary interface and classes to test, we have a 
choice on how to use them.

First. we could simply pass the delegate (the real and the fake) to the 
class....

So we need to change our class by adding a new constructor parameter and 
changing how it calls exit.

public class SomethingThatCallsExit {

   private SystemExiter systemExiter;

   public SomethingThatCallsExit( SystemExiter exiter) {
       systemExiter = exiter;
   }

   public int add(int num1, int num2) {
       if( num1 &lt; 0) {
          //System.exit(2);
         exiter.exit(2);
      }
      return num1 + num2;
   }

}

Now we can test it like so...

public class SomethingThatCallsExitTests extends Testcase {

  public void testTryingToAddNegativeNumberStopsApp () {
      FakeSystemExiter exiter = new FakeSystemExiter();
      SomethingThatCallsExit calc = new SomethingThatCallsExit ( exiter  );

      calc.add( -1 , 1);

     assertTrue(&quot;Exit not called!&quot;, exiter.wasExitCalled );    
  }
}

This does mean that the application code that creates and uses the class 
under test (not shown here) would need to be modified to pass the 
constructor parameter.

This is a nice and clean way of setting the delegate though.


The second approach is useful if we can&#39;t (don&#39;t want to) change the 
code that creates and uses our class under test. This means our class 
under test has to create the real exiter itself and during testing we 
need to use a hook into this creation, so we can over ride it and 
provide our fake.

First lets rewrite the class so it creates the exiter....

public class SomethingThatCallsExit {

   public int add(int num1, int num2) {
       if( num1 &lt; 0) {
          //System.exit(2);
          SystemExiter systemExiter = createExiter();
         exiter.exit(2);
      }
      return num1 + num2;
   }

  // real implementation
   protected SystemExiter createExiter() {
      return new RealSystemExiter();
   }

}


Now lets write the test to over ride the &#39;createExiter()&#39; method to 
return our fake.

public class SomethingThatCallsExitTests extends Testcase {

    public class TestableSomethingThatCallsExit extends  
SomethingThatCallsExit{

         protected SystemExiter createExiter() {
             return systemExiter;
         }

    }



  public void testTryingToAddNegativeNumberStopsApp () {
      systemExiter = new FakeSystemExiter();
      TestableSomethingThatCallsExit calc = new 
TestableSomethingThatCallsExit ();

      calc.add( -1 , 1);

     assertTrue(&quot;Exit not called!&quot;, exiter.wasExitCalled );    
  }
}



So there you go....two ways of injecting a fake exiter into the class 
under test, so that we can test it without the real System.exit() being 
called.

HTH

Andrew


